Program 3 — Map of Account by Id (the auto-keying constructor)

// The idiomatic shortcut: pass a query straight into the Map<Id, sObject>
// constructor and it auto-keys every record by its Id.
Map<Id, Account> accById = new Map<Id, Account>(
    [SELECT Id, Name, Industry FROM Account LIMIT 10]
);

System.debug('Accounts loaded: ' + accById.size());
System.debug('All Ids (keySet): ' + accById.keySet());

// O(1) lookup by Id
for (Id accId : accById.keySet()) {
    Account a = accById.get(accId);
    System.debug(a.Name + ' | ' + a.Industry);
}

// .get() on a missing key returns null (it does NOT throw)
Id fakeId = '001000000000000AAA';
Account missing = accById.get(fakeId);
System.debug('Missing lookup: ' + missing);   // null

// values() gives you a List<Account> when you need to iterate or DML them
List<Account> allAccts = accById.values();
System.debug('Values count: ' + allAccts.size());

If your org has no Accounts, this loads nothing — create one first (insert new Account(Name='Test');) or the map will be empty.
